= lesson 16: society

We live in a society! Let's learn some words that are useful for navigating a
society:

#list((
  word("уұӨҹ", "kulupu", "community, team, group"),
  word("уұӨҝ", "nasin", "way, method, tradition, path"),
  word("уұӨӢ", "esun", "to swap, to trade; market, shop"),
  word("уұӨІ", "mani", "money, valuable thing"),
  word("уұӨ·", "moli", "dead; to kill"),
  word("уұӨј", "mute", "many, very"),
))

Let's use the new words in sentences:

#list((
  sentence("уұӨҝуұӨјуұӨ§уұӨ¬", "nasin mute li lon.", "There are many traditions."),
  sentence("уұӨ‘уұӨ§уұҘүуұӨ¬уұӨҹ", "jan li pali lon kulupu.", "People work in teams."),
  sentence(
    "уұӨҘуұҘ”уұӨ§уұҘ·уұӨүуұӨІуұӨј",
    "len pona li wile e mani mute.",
    "Good clothes require a lot of money.
Good clothes are expensive.",
  ),
  sentence(
    "уұӨ‘уұӨјуұӨ§уұӨ·уұҘ§уұҘұуұҘЈ",
    "jan mute li moli tan utala suli.",
    "Many people died because of the war.",
  ),
  sentence(
    "уұӨҙуұҘ·уұӨӢуұӨүуұҘўуұӨҙ",
    "mi wile esun e soweli mi.",
    "I would like to sell my cow.",
  ),
  sentence(
    "уұӨҙуұҘ·уұӨӮуұӨӢуұӨүуұҘўуұҘһ",
    "mi wile ala esun e soweli sina.",
    "I don't want to buy your cow.",
  ),
))

Here is something fun you might notice: #strong[уұӨӢ esun] generally means 'to
swap', but there's enough information in the sentences to know that it
specifically means 'to sell' in one sentence, and 'to buy' in another!

== more about mute

#strong[уұӨј mute] is a very useful word to have. We don't see adjectives attach to
pronouns #strong[уұӨҙ mi], #strong[уұҘһ sina], #strong[уұҘҶ ona] all that often, but
#strong[уұӨј mute] is so useful that it does that quite frequently:

#list((
  word("уұӨҙуұӨј", "mi mute", "we, many of us"),
  sentence(
    "уұӨҹуұҘүуұӨ§уұӨ“уұӨүуұӨҙуұӨј",
    "kulupu pali li jo e mi mute.",
    "The labour union includes a lot of us.",
  ),
  word("уұҘһуұӨј", "sina mute", "you lot, you guys, y'all"),
  sentence(
    "уұҘҶуұӨ§уұӨҳуұҘ уұӨүуұҘһуұӨј",
    "ona li ken sitelen e sina mute.",
    "They can take a picture of you guys.",
  ),
))

Remember the special rule that says: "when #strong[уұӨҙ mi] or #strong[уұҘһ sina] is
the subject of the sentence, we remove the #strong[уұӨ§ li]"? That rule is quite
specific! Take a look at these sentences:

#list((
  sentence("уұӨҙуұӨјуұӨ§уұӨ•уұӨ»", "mi mute li kalama musi.", "We perform music together."),
  sentence("уұҘһуұӨјуұӨ§уұҘЎуұӨүуұҘҒ", "sina mute li sona e ni.", "Many of you know this."),
))

Notice how the #strong[уұӨ§ li] isn't dropped. This is because the subject isn't
either #strong[уұӨҙ mi] or #strong[уұҘһ sina], but instead #strong[уұӨҙуұӨј mi mute] and
#strong[уұҘһуұӨј sina mute]!

It might seem like an odd quirk, but remember --- the purpose of #strong[уұӨ§ li]
is to show where the verb starts! If it was dropped here, we would instead
assume #strong[уұӨј mute] is the verb.

